{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614206"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16353"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16353"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0,0.19,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116479"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9044"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98478"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7193"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21508"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21510"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe extraocular muscles are responsible for eye movement and are innervated by different cranial nerves. One cranial nerve in particular controls most of these movements.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves innervates the inferior oblique muscles of the eye?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CN III (oculomotor)","CN II (optic)","CN IV (trochlear)","CN V (trigeminal)","CN VII (facial)"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor nerve (CN III)\u003C/strong\u003E innervates four of the six extraocular muscles: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, and inferior oblique. It also innervates the levator palpebrae superioris muscle which raises the upper eyelid. Additionally, it carries parasympathetic fibres to the sphincter pupillae and ciliary muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic nerve (CN II)\u003C/strong\u003E is purely sensory and carries visual information from the retina to the brain. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochlear nerve (CN IV)\u003C/strong\u003E only innervates the superior oblique muscle. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve (CN V)\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the face and motor innervation to the muscles of mastication. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve (CN VII)\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the muscles of facial expression and carries taste fibres from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III) innervates the superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, inferior oblique muscles of the eye, and the levator palpebrae superioris.","The oculomotor nerve also carries parasympathetic fibres that control pupillary constriction and lens accommodation."],"references":["Sanders RD. Cranial Nerves III, IV, and VI: Oculomotor Function. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2009 Nov;6(11):34-9. PMID: 20049149; PMCID: PMC2801485.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98478"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16353"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98478"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9044"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116479"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0